{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641181"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17867"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24668"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe regulation of fatty acid oxidation involves multiple enzymes and regulatory molecules that respond to cellular energy status. Understanding these pathways is crucial for comprehending metabolic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the regulation of fatty acid oxidation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["AMP-activated protein kinase activation occurs during energy surplus","Phosphorylation activates acetyl-CoA carboxylase","Malonyl-CoA is an allosteric inhibitor of carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1","Active acetyl-CoA carboxylase decreases malonyl-CoA production","Carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 activity increases with malonyl-CoA"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalonyl-CoA is an allosteric inhibitor of carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a key regulatory step in fatty acid oxidation. By inhibiting CPT-1, malonyl-CoA prevents the transport of fatty acids into the mitochondria, thus reducing their oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAMP-activated protein kinase activation occurs during energy surplus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as AMPK is actually activated during energy deficit, not surplus. \u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphorylation activates acetyl-CoA carboxylase\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because phosphorylation by AMPK inactivates ACC. \u003Cstrong\u003EActive acetyl-CoA carboxylase decreases malonyl-CoA production\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since active ACC increases malonyl-CoA production. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 activity increases with malonyl-CoA\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as CPT-1 is inhibited by malonyl-CoA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis regulatory system ensures that fatty acid oxidation is suppressed when energy status is high (elevated malonyl-CoA) and enhanced when energy status is low (reduced malonyl-CoA via AMPK activation).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Malonyl-CoA is an allosteric inhibitor of carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 (CPT-1), preventing fatty acid entry into mitochondria for oxidation.","AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) is activated by low energy states, leading to inhibition of acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) and reduced malonyl-CoA levels.","Phosphorylation of ACC by AMPK inactivates ACC, reducing malonyl-CoA production and promoting fatty acid oxidation."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:36:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:37:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{